{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}} {{Use British English|date=June 2016}} {{Infobox film | name = Duet for One | image = Duetforoneposter.jpg | caption = Theatrical release poster | director = [[Andrei Konchalovsky]] | writer = [[Tom Kempinski]] | starring = {{plainlist| * [[Julie Andrews]] * [[Alan Bates]] * [[Max von Sydow]] * [[Rupert Everett]] }} | distributor = [[Golan-Globus|Golan-Globus Productions Ltd.]] | released =25 December 1986 <ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/alphabetical.htm?letter=D&page=6&p=.htm |title=Alphabetical Movie Index, A-Z |publisher=Boxofficemojo.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref> | runtime = 107 minutes | country = United Kingdom | language = English |gross= $8,736 <ref>{{Mojo title|duetforone}}</ref> }} '''''Duet for One''''' is a 1986 British [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] adapted from the play, a [[two-hander]] by [[Tom Kempinski]], about a world-famous concert violinist named Stephanie Anderson who is suddenly struck with [[multiple sclerosis]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-05-23/entertainment/ca-8319_1_theater |title=The Diminuendo Of 'Duet For One' - Los Angeles Times |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=1985-05-23 |accessdate=2013-09-28 |first=Lawrence |last=Christon}}</ref> It is set in London, and directed by [[Andrei Konchalovsky]]. The story is based on the life of cellist [[Jacqueline du Pr√©]], who was diagnosed with MS, and her husband, conductor [[Daniel Barenboim]], and only marginally fictionalized.
==Synopsis== Stephanie Anderson, a world-famous violinist, becomes unable to play because of multiple sclerosis. A depressed psychiatrist she sees is unable to help with her rage and frustration. Her star pupil, realizing he will learn nothing more, leaves her. Her husband departs with his young secretary, and her accompanist dies. Her fierce desire to be alone in her pain alienates everybody except her faithful maid. She gives all her musical effects to a totter (an itinerant scrap merchant), who she asks into her bed as well. Watching a videotape of a concert triumph, she takes an overdose but the maid breaks in to try and save her. In an epilogue, which may be a dream, the psychiatrist has become a friend while her ex-husband and former pupil come back to see her, as does the ghost of her accompanist.
==Primary cast== *[[Julie Andrews]]: Stephanie Anderson<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-02-08/entertainment/ca-970_1_multiple-sclerosis |title=Clarifying A Few Facts About Ms, 'Duet For One' - Los Angeles Times |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=2007-08-02 |accessdate=2013-09-28 |first=Laura R. |last=Mitchell}}</ref> *[[Alan Bates]]: David Cornwallis *[[Max von Sydow]]: Dr. Louis Feldman *[[Rupert Everett]]: Constantine Kassanis *[[Margaret Courtenay (actress)|Margaret Courtenay]]: Sonia Randvich *[[Cathryn Harrison]]: Penny Smallwood *[[Sigfrit Steiner]]: Leonid Lefimov *[[Macha M√©ril]]: Anya *[[Liam Neeson]]: Totter *[[Siobhan Redmond]]: Totter's wife *[[Paula Figgett]]: Totter's Daughter
==Reception== The movie gained positive reviews.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-12-25/entertainment/ca-572_1_julie-andrews |title=Movie Review: 'Duet For One': A Four-hankie Drama Of The Past - Los Angeles Times |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=1986-12-25 |accessdate=2013-09-28 |first=Kevin |last=Thomas}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Maslin |first=Janet |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B0DE2D6113DF930A25751C0A961948260 |title=Movie Review - Duet For One - FILM: 'DUET FOR ONE' - NYTimes.com |publisher=Movies.nytimes.com |date=1987-02-13 |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert |first=Roger |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/duet-for-one-1987 |title=Duet for One Movie Review & Film Summary (1987) |publisher=Roger Ebert |date=2013-09-20 |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref>
==Awards== [[Golden Globe]] for Best Actress in a Drama Role: Julie Andrews (Nominated)<ref>[https://archive.is/20130928234402/http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GolWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YEENAAAAIBAJ&pg=1312,1341910&dq=golden+globe+for+best+actress+julie+andrews+duet+for+one&hl=en] </ref>
==Stage play== ''Duet for One'' premiered at the [[Bush Theatre]] in 1980 with [[Frances de la Tour]] and [[David de Keyser]] in the leading roles. Kempinski and de la Tour were married at the time, and he wrote the role with her in mind. It had successful runs in the [[West End theatre|West End]] and on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-02-23/entertainment/ca-1222_1_stage-manager |title=Stage Review: A Gripping Duel For Two In 'Duet For One' - Los Angeles Times |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=1985-02-23 |accessdate=2013-09-28 |first=Dan |last=Sullivan}}</ref> A major revival was staged by the [[Almeida Theatre]] in 2009, starring [[Juliet Stevenson]] and [[Henry Goodman]]. This revival too was lauded by the critics, and it subsequently transferred to the [[Vaudeville Theatre]] in the West End.<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Billington |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2009/jan/30/review-almeida-duet-for-one |title=Theatre review: Duet For One / Almeida, London &#124; Stage |publisher=The Guardian |date=2009-01-30 |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref>
