'''''Motor Madness''''' was a motorsports based [[television show]] on [[Spike TV|The Nashville Network]] debuted in 1997.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/wichita/stories/1998/04/13/daily4.html "TNN brings big money back"] ''Wichita Business Journal''. 8-26-2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.pageant.com/autumnsmith/page3.html "Autumn Smith  talks to Patrick Nathaniel Bartholomew III"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117230531/http://pageant.com/autumnsmith/page3.html |date=2011-11-17 }} ''Pageant News Bureau''. 8-26-2013.</ref> It was originally formatted as a live, 3 hour show with a studio segment and coverage of a live event.  Racing events included [[USA Motorsports]] [[monster trucks]], [[demolition derby|demolition derbies]], [[tractor pull]]s, [[swamp buggy|swamp buggies]], and either live pacers awards or upcoming previews of CBS motorsports properties‚Äîthe [[World of Outlaws]] [[sprint car racing|Sprint Series]], [[American Speed Association]] ACDelco Challenge Series, the [[Sprint Cup Series|NASCAR Winston Cup Series]], [[Nationwide Series|NASCAR Busch Grand National Series]], and the [[Camping World Truck Series|NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series]].

In the second season (1998), the studio segments were replaced with live antics involving the announcers, due to the pregnancy of one of the show's studio segment hosts, Katie Haas.  Many fans were angered at the change, and the show's live format was canceled.  The name lived on for a few more seasons in a change to the ''[[Monster Jam]]'' monster truck exclusive format, then was completely abandoned for the Monster Jam moniker.

